  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What shall I do with a mouse which freezes on the screen and stop responding?",
  "response": "If your mouse cursor freezes on the screen and stops responding, try these troubleshooting steps to resolve the issue:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Check the Basics**\n- **Check the USB connection**: If it's a wired mouse, unplug and replug it into the USB port. Try a different USB port if possible.\n- **Check the battery**: If it's a wireless mouse, ensure the battery is charged or replace it.\n- **Check the receiver**: For wireless mice, ensure the receiver is properly connected.\n- **Clean the mouse**: Dust or debris can interfere with the sensor (especially on optical mice).\n\n---\n\n### **2. Restart Your Computer**\nA restart can resolve temporary software glitches that may be causing the mouse to freeze.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Try Another Mouse**\n- Connect a different mouse to your computer. If the new mouse works, the issue is likely with your original mouse.\n- If the new mouse also doesn\u2019t work, the problem may be with your computer\u2019s hardware or drivers.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Update or Reinstall Mouse Drivers**\n- **On Windows**:\n  1. Open **Device Manager** (right-click the Start menu > Device Manager).\n  2. Expand **Mice and other pointing devices**.\n  3. Right-click your mouse and select **Update driver**.\n  4. Alternatively, select **Uninstall device**, then restart your computer to reinstall the driver automatically.\n- **On Mac**:\n  1. Apple usually handles mouse drivers automatically, but you can try resetting the SMC (System Management Controller) or NVRAM (non-volatile random-access memory) to resolve hardware issues.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Check for Software Conflicts**\n- Close any applications that might be causing the issue (e.g., screen-sharing software or remote access tools).\n- Disable third-party mouse customization software (e.g., Logitech G HUB, Razer Synapse) to see if it resolves the issue.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Test in Safe Mode**\n- Boot your computer in **Safe Mode** to see if the mouse works. If it does, the issue is likely caused by a third-party application or driver.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Test on Another Computer**\n- Connect the mouse to another computer to see if it works there. If it doesn\u2019t, the mouse itself may be faulty.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Check for System Updates**\nEnsure your operating system is up to date, as updates often include fixes for hardware and driver issues.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Repair or Replace the Mouse**\nIf none of the above steps work and the issue persists, the mouse may be damaged and needs repair or replacement.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to diagnose and resolve the issue with your frozen mouse.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
